there's not really a right or wrong way to music. if people like the song, you did it the right way. there's lots of "rules" for producing, but rules are made to be bent and sometimes broken entirely. me personally, i only use like 3 fx on my master fx chain. less is more imo.

i'd say get really good at getting great sound with 3 basic plugins. EQ, Compression, and Reverb. those are like salt pepper and garlic. i don't think there's an album made since 1950 that DIDN'T use those fx. They're essential. practice getting good sounds from just those three, the branch out. that's just my opinion.

posts.com:
>>114148670

here is your masterclass:

1. never put anything on master, ever, leave that for... mastering.
2. high pass literally everything, but do so subtly; too much will remove the character of the sound.
3. add subtle saturation/distortion to all of your busses. yes, really, everything. subtle distortion generates upper harmonics, which means you can get away with carving off more low end to make room in the mix without losing the sound of the track. (make sure you apply distortion BEFORE eq'ing however)
4. use busses/groups to group and effect similar tracks.
5. use LCR mixing; double (or triple) tracking takes and panning them hard R/L (and center if you're triple tracking) is a really powerful technique that generates good stereo image; be careful of phase though, and monitor in mono to make sure compatibility is good.
6. use compression; use it basically everywhere. learning how to dial in a compressor is an art, and should be done in a subtle way.
7. use parallel processing. this ties in with the last point. every bus should have a rack of effects in parallel (in ableton, this is called an "Audio Effect Rack"). in general, each rack should have 1. a clean signal 2. a compressed signal, and 3. a 100% wet reverb signal. you can of course add other effects. generally speaking, my busses typically look like: distortion -> EQ -> parallel processing rack described above.
8. use targeted bell filters in your EQ to bring out instruments in your mix; make sure different part don't have the same frequency ranges accentuated however.

digesting and internalizing this will get you a long, long way. some people may disagree with certain parts of this, but this is the stuff i wish i knew a very long time ago.

From Genesis to Revelation is Moody Blues-inspired folkpop
Trespass and Nursery Cryme are where they get more proggy but still within the folk realm. A lot more somber in my opinion. Wonderful storytelling. Their most underrated stuff
Foxtrot and Selling England By The Pound is still similar to their other stuff but a lot more theatric (using elements of music hall for example), their classical music inspiration being a lot more upfront as well, and more rock-oriented (psychedelic rock and of course progressive rock), but still within their British folk roots as far as overall sound and storytelling/lyricism goes. This is the fan favorite era.

I see HIP less as a competitor to the way classical music is performed in general and more as an experiment in trying to emulate the past. They're two different markets that touch upon the same type of work. Most HIP focuses on baroque music and uses the harpsichord and viola. Instruments that have a different vibe and feel compared to their successors. It is only natural that certain groups would like to revive that feeling only those instruments could provide. However, HIP can delve into the realm of the autist if it's something like refusing to play Beethoven on anything other than a fortepiano. Again, I don't believe that HIP is really doing anything that harmful.

posts.com: If, on the other hand, we estimate the worth of the Beautiful Arts by the culture they supply to the mind, and take as a standard the expansion of the faculties which must concur in the Judgement for cognition, Music will have the lowest place among them (as it has perhaps the highest among those arts which are valued for their pleasantness), because it merely plays with sensations. The formative arts are far before it in this point of view; for in putting the Imagination in a free play, which is also accordant with the Understanding, they at the same time carry on a serious business. This they do by producing a product that serves for concepts as a permanent self-commendatory vehicle for promoting their union with sensibility and thus, as it were, the urbanity of the higher cognitive powers. These two species of art take quite different courses; the first proceeds from sensations to indeterminate Ideas, the second from determinate Ideas to sensations. The latter produce permanent, the former only transitory impressions. The Imagination can recall the one and entertain itself pleasantly therewith; but the other either vanish entirely, or if they are recalled involuntarily by the Imagination they are rather wearisome than pleasant. Besides, there attaches to Music a certain want of urbanity from the fact that, chiefly from the character of its instruments, it extends its influence further than is desired (in the neighbourhood), and so as it were obtrudes itself, and does violence to the freedom of others who are not of the musical company. The Arts which appeal to the eyes do not do this; for we need only turn our eyes away, if we wish to avoid being impressed. The case of music is almost like that of the delight derived from a smell that diffuses itself widely. The man who pulls his perfumed handkerchief out of his pocket attracts the attention of all round him, even against their will, and he forces them, if they are to breathe at all, to enjoy the scent;

>>114111683
Toscanini was a very variable conductor like any one else. It's important to realize that we only really know him for the end of his career - that is with the NBC Orchestra and those late 30s-early 50s recordings. He was more critically acclaimed for his tenure with the New York Philharmonic, of which we have far fewer recordings (and the few that we do have are in pretty bad sound). The recordings that are in listenable shape reveal a more flexible conductor, especially outside of classical-era repertoire.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114102256
>best amp sim for guitar and/or bass? maybe i'm just retarded but i can't get a good tone out of logic's default ones.
I have used Logic's amps and I found that for a hard rock/metal tone, I needed to do a couple of EQ moves. I think I did this.
1. High shelf boost before the amp.
2. Pretty big mid-scoop after the amp.
3. Pretty big bass boost around 70-100hz, depending on your tuning.
4. High-cut the really bright frequencies, at least above 10k, but possibly even lower than that.
5. You might want a boost around 6k for brightness.
6. Precise notch cuts to dampen resonant frequencies.

Remember that amp sims are really just algorithmic distortion and filters in a box. You can usually get a good tone out of anything with conscious EQ moves.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114125247
I remember the built-in tutorials being decent in 2012. They're probably at least as good now. Sorry I don't have more current info, but here are some very important hotkeys for starters:

>"Tab" switches between horizontal (arrangement) and vertical (session) views
>"Tab" + "Shift" switches between effects view on the bottom and edit view for the selected clip

Also, you'll want to download/install ASIO4ALL if you're on a PC, then set it as your audio driver in the settings menu. It'll help get you lower latency than default Windows drivers.

Last thing - learn where the "record arm" buttons are if you wanna record stuff. In the vertical view, you can click the little record circles for each clip space. If you wanna record to the main timeline, press F9 or click the record button up top. Good luck anon

posts.com:
>>114146088
Are you using an HDD or SSD? Do you have a separate drive for installing programs? My laptop could never run larger kontakt instruments, specifically drumlab, but now I have a desktop where the OS is on an m.2 drive, apps on an SSD, and recording/re-writable data on an HDD. Projects utilizing Kontakt instruments still increase the amount of time it takes to open a project, but it works.

Also, quick tip for everybody: if you only have one drive in your production machine, it should be an SSD. Whether you have a laptop, or a desktop, get an SSD. If you try to play live with an HDD, standing waves will destroy your system over time and cause glitches while you're on stage. And if you're running a laptop with only one drive, and you're trying to render/write audio while you're also reading audio from a kontakt instrument, you're gonna have a bad time. Any plugin that involves a sample library larger than 1GB is probably gonna make your computer scream if you're on a budget system.

>>114155950
Depends on the connection. An internal pcie drive will always be the fastest, so it's optimal for streaming, which makes it best for playing/midi playback for large sample library instruments. Thunderbolt is also really fast. But if you're using USB, that might slow it down to where you get skips in your playback. Depending on just how much latency the USB causes, you might get something that's only a minor issue that's tolerable while producing, but unacceptable for a live show.

>>114143688
Things you need to do a decent job of it:
-allen keys (both metric and imperial) and the gibson truss rod wrench if you have a gibson
-you need both metric and imperial because some brands mix and match on the same guitar. Truss rod metric, bridge saddles imperial, for example.
-capo
-phillips screwdriver
-feeler gauges
-something that measures in 64th inch or 0.5mm for action
-a tuner you can plug in to. clip-ons aren't great for doing intonation
Things you need for a complete setup that may involve fret levelling, nut filing, nut replacement:
-nut slot files
-crowning file or make a safe edged three corner file
-fret dressing file for fret ends/tangs (the three corner file works for this too)
-slotted straight edge in the scale you need for what you're working on
-sanding beam (hardware store level with double sided tape works fine for this)
-skinny chisels if you're replacing the nut. You need these to clean the old glue out of the gap first before putting in new nut
-bunch of sandpaper
-soldering iron and associated stuff for electronics work

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114149287
leaving it strung isnt bad. in fact, its good to keep some pressure on the neck while in storage. That can keep the neck from twisting. What you should consider is whether the wood has dried out, acoustics can be sensitive to humidity, ir lack of. Try to get it in a room at 45-65% relative humidity for a couple days. Then I would go ahead and replace all the strings, those are pretty old and likely have corrosion settling in

Just go in and look at the acoustics in your price range first. When they ask you if you need help say no. Find 2 or 3 you like, and then ask the clerks about them if you need more info. Check out the looks first, neck profile/feel, frets, action, body shape, etc. If the clerk recommends something you didn't see or try, try it as well, but don't up your price based on what the employee says.

Lauren Eve Mayberry (born 7 October 1987) is a Scottish singer, musician and songwriter. She is the vocalist and percussionist of the Scottish pop band Chvrches.[8] In Chvrches, Mayberry co-writes and co-produces the songs with Iain Cook and Martin Doherty, and sings as the lead vocalist. She also plays drums and keyboards. Mayberry is a soprano.[9][10][11][12]

Early life and education

Mayberry was born in 1987 in Thornhill, Stirling. She has played the piano since she was a child and drums since she was a teenager.[13]

Mayberry attended Beaconhurst School (now known as Fairview International School) an independent school in Bridge of Allan. She also lived in Gladstone, Illinois as a foreign-exchange student.[14] After completing a four-year undergraduate law degree at the University of Strathclyde, she earned a master's degree in journalism in 2010.[15][16] This led her into a career in freelance journalism and production running. From 2009 to 2010 she was a contributor[17] to the UK music website The Line of Best Fit.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Would? is such a fucking powerful song, and I'd argue a contender for one of the bleakest Alice in Chains songs lyrically speaking.
It's about the absolute death of freewill at the hands of addiction and relapse, and comparing something like that to getting caught up in a flood that's going to kill you and getting pulled back by the current just when you think you're getting better.
Then it asks in the very last line to consider whether or not something like that could happen to you; to just consider that for moment and to have some empathy.
Its meaning is only compounded by the fact that it's the closing track off Dirt; foreshadowing that there wasn't ever going to be a shred of hope, and that tragedy was inevitable.
Sure a lot of AIC fan are people who struggle with drug and substance abuse, but that's only because songs like this fill them with a much needed dose of existential horror.
If anything, it should scare people into getting as clean while they're able to.

posts.com:
Drugs can definitely enhance the listening experience, especially when it comes to spiritual music. I’d say the secular use of drugs while listening to, say, pop music is quite a different experience than using drugs while listening to ambient, folk, or drone music. Historically speaking, substances have ALWAYS been taken in combination with live music. These practices have always been around and date into prehistory. Yes, alcohol is a drug so having a few beers at a live concert can be placed into this category. The hashish smokers of ancient Iran would play live music, as do the datura cults in South America, the Vodouisants of Haiti drink heavily while playing their music, and the list can go on and on. The anons itt mocking this practice should be a little more open minded on this subject, but I can agree to the extent that the secular chronic use of marijuana isn’t very respectable.
Tl/dr:
Drugs are based but should be taken with care and respect

>>114102843
Viperman again

>>114102823
Listened to the whole album
That beat drop on track 4 was really good, wasnt expecting that. Those drums and synthd make me think of Orchestral Manouevres at the Dark. Maybe my favorite part of this EP
Vocals are a bit buried in all tracks. Nice bass on track 2. Track 1 isnt really a strong opener to the album I think.
Something about the tracks overall make me not really get into the vibe of the album and engage with it completely. It seems a bit monotonous maybe, like the album is just going through the motions and no part is really different than another. For example, track 2 has a synth solo but when it hapoens everything else (bass, guitar, back synth, drums especially) is just doing the same thing they were already doing. That can be me not being familiar with the style, but I feel the tracks would be better with something to grab the listener. Maybe develop the ideas you have in the arrangement a bit, what I get from it is no moment really standing out. It could help giving some relief (in the architectural sense). Track 3 for example is a bit better in this regard, but even with some cool different synth stuff being introduced the rest of it is still is very much of the same and the vocals being buried doesnt help.
Anyway I like the elements here I just think they could fit together in a better way. Im also not a huge fan of the vague/suggestive lyrics
The final track is a good album closer, maybe the guitar could let itself go a bit tho and play around the synth. But the guitar notes complement the synths really well here

I really can't convince you if your mind is already made up, but greatest hits compilations like Hot Rocks one and two are good places to start for their sixties hits. Also Through The Past, Darkly, along with High Tides and Green Grass.

As far as actual albums, I like Now, Between The Buttons, Out of Our Heads, Flowers, Her Satanic Majesty's Request, and Get Yer Ya Yas Out (The last one is a concert album)

Many people prefer The Beatles over The Rolling Stones, so this list might not change your mind, but, as a die hard Beatle-Maniac myself, these are Rolling Stones albums I find quite enjoyable. The sort of lost me after Let It Bleed, so I won't recommend any of the post 60s albums, or any albums made after Brian Jones died.

Mud Slide Slim and the Blue Horizon [Warner Bros., 1971]
If even his admirers acknowledge that his music has lost some of its drive (lost some of its drive?), then even a sworn enemy can admit that he's capable of interesting songs and intricate music. Having squandered most of the songs on his big success, he's concentrating on the intricate music--the lyrics are more onanistic than ever, escapist as a matter of conscious thematic decision. From what? you well may wonder. From success, poor fella. Blues singers lived on the road out of economic necessity, although they often got into it; Taylor is an addict, pure and simple. A born-rich nouveau star who veers between a "homestead on the farm" (what does he raise there, hopes?) and the Holiday Inn his mean old existential dilemma compels him to call home deserves the conniving, self-pitying voice that is his curse. Interesting, intricate, unlistenable. C+

it's almost unique because of the process

because Beefheart composed it by playing a piano even though he didn't know how to play (because he'd seen Zappa compose like that) and Drumbo writing down the things that Beefheart thought sounded good and arranging them for the Magic Band and then that weird stuff was meticulously rehearsed so the band could recreate it

it's very rare that music on record retains that spontaneous feel of just randomly jamming coming up with neat stuff and is disciplined enough so that it's tight and repeatable

Beefheart's concept was just to combine blues rock with avant-garde/free jazz influences, but it's really the combination of unusual compositions that were actually arranged and rehearsed that makes the album
